1 (6) Biometric, health, or medical data, or insurance information; and
2 (7) School or employment location.
3 2. A person is guilty of disseminating personally identifying information if, with the intent
4 to intimidate, abuse, threaten, harass, or frighten an individual who resides in the
5 state:
6 a. The person intentionally disseminates the personally identifying information of an
7 individual or that individual's immediate family member or household member;
8 and
9 b. The dissemination would reasonably cause an individual to be in fear of physical
10 injury to themselves, or to the individual's immediate family member or household
11 member.
12 3. This section applies to all electronic communications originating within or accessible
13 within the state.
14 4. Disseminating personally identifying information is a class A misdemeanor, unless the
15 dissemination results in:
16 a. Bodily injury to the individual or to the individual's immediate family member or
17 household member, in which case it is a class C felony;
18 b. Substantial or serious bodily injury to the individual or to the individual's
19 immediate family member or household member, in which case it is a class B
20 felony; or
21 c. Death of the individual or of the individual's immediate family member or
22 household member, in which case it is a class A felony.
23 SECTION 2. EMERGENCY. This Act is declared to be an emergency measure.
